  "text": "To evaluate possibile paratenic hosts that can develop larva migrans, [CITATION_1] , experimentally inoculated Mongolian gerbils. Exposure of gerbils to 100e4000 embryonated eggs resulted in VLM, but no larvae were found in the brain. A squirrel monkey (Saimiri sciureus) inoculated with 10,000 B. potosis eggs did not develop clinical signs or gross lesions, although a few migrating larvae were recovered from liver and kidney tissues [CITATION_2] . Another squirrel monkey inoculated with 100,000 eggs in the same trial developed gross lesions, including liver congestion, pulmonary edema, and abundant intestinal granulomas. Small granulomatous lesions containing larvae were found in the outer layers of the cerebral cortex, without deeper invasion as is typical of B. procyonis. This animal was found dead at 30 DPI, but the animal lacked clinical signs and the authors state that no cause of death was determined. However, pulmonary edema, liver congestion, and nodular lesions containing non-degenerate larvae along the intestine were found at necropsy [CITATION_3] . Based on these preliminary trials, it appears that B. potosis can cause larva migrans in rodent and primate hosts, although the pathogenicity and capacity for neural invasion appears less than that of B. procyonis or B. columnaris.",
